### 2. QUIC in Space: Initial Measurements and Analysis
* **Presentation:** [QUIC in space](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/126/materials/slides-126-anrw-transport-and-media-quic-in-space-00)
* **Presenter:** Natalia Petroski
* **Discussion:**
  * Natalia Petroski evaluated the performance of QUIC implementations (Quinn and Quiche) in deep space scenarios (lunar communication and beyond) characterized by high round-trip times (RTTs of 1s, 3s, and 6s) and intermittent connectivity.
  * The evaluation analyzed two protocol extensions:
    * **ACK Frequency:** Aimed at delaying acknowledgments on highly asymmetrical links. Results showed no significant flow completion time improvements in the evaluated deep space scenarios.
    * **Careful Resume (`draft-ietf-tcpm-careful-resume`):** Caches congestion control parameters to bypass slow start. This showed performance benefits in Quiche, but encountered implementation issues in Quinn (specifically with BBR).
  * Outage recovery tests showed that Quinn utilizing Cubic struggled to recover at lower RTTs due to burst-sending behaviors.
  * **Q&A:**
    * Gorry Fairhurst noted that timing and recovery anomalies are common when stress-testing protocol implementations under these conditions. He asked if they had evaluated Happy Eyeballs racing QUIC against TCP; Natalia Petroski responded that they had not.
    * Robert inquired about the simulated bottleneck link data rate of 25 Mbps. Natalia Petroski explained that this was based on the intersatellite link rate of Iridium satellites.
    * Danish asked how simulated link outages aligned with BBR's internal probing phases (bandwidth/RTT probing). Natalia Petroski clarified that the study did not coordinate the timing of outages with specific BBR phases.

### 3. u and i: H3 Prioritization for Cooperative Scheduling in MASQUE
* **Presentation:** [u and i](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/126/materials/slides-126-anrw-transport-and-media-u-and-i-00)
* **Presenter:** Daniel
* **Discussion:**
  * Daniel presented how the HTTP/3 Extensible Prioritization Scheme (EPS)—using the urgency (`u`) and incremental (`i`) parameters—can enable cooperative scheduling in MASQUE proxies.
  * The authors developed **Mask NADA** (built on Tokyo Quiche), a pluggable scheduling framework allowing clients to dynamically request custom schedulers at the proxy.
  * Testing showed that while unreliable MASQUE tunnels lose EPS semantics (as they apply only to streams), reliable tunnels successfully utilized the urgency parameter to reduce completion times. An "EPS-aware" scheduler was implemented to prevent starvation by selectively yielding high-priority opportunities to lower-priority flows.
  * **Q&A:**
    * Lucas Pardew commented on the complexity of combining signaling with downstream proxy scheduling, especially with QUIC datagrams, and highlighted ongoing IETF draft work targeting datagram priorities. Daniel acknowledged this and mentioned related student work exploring prioritization over datagrams.

### 4. QUIC as a Multiplexing Layer in WebRTC
* **Presentation:** [QUIC as Multiplexing Layer in WebRTC](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/126/materials/slides-126-anrw-transport-and-media-quic-as-multiplexing-layer-in-webrtc-00)
* **Presenter:** Matthijs Engelbart
* **Discussion:**
  * Matthijs Engelbart proposed an alternative WebRTC transport architecture that multiplexes both media and data channels over a single QUIC connection. This prevents the standard SCTP-over-DTLS data channels from starving the concurrently running RTP streams.
  * The implementation utilizes the RTP over QUIC specification (`draft-ietf-avtcore-rtp-over-quic`) alongside a custom data channel protocol mapped to QUIC.
  * By utilizing a single congestion controller (GCC-based) with the packet receive timestamp extension, the architecture dynamically shares bandwidth, reserving a portion for media (prioritizing media packets to minimize latency and jitter) and allowing data channels to consume the remaining elastic capacity.
  * **Q&A:**
    * Gorry Fairhurst asked if they evaluated partial reliability; Matthijs Engelbart responded that they utilized QUIC streams with timeouts to cancel late retransmissions, rather than fully customized partial reliability mechanisms.
    * Francois Michel asked if this architecture could be mapped to WebTransport for easier browser deployment. Matthijs Engelbart indicated that while the current draft is strictly defined for QUIC, it could be extended to WebTransport.
    * Dirk Kutscher clarified that the prototype used QUIC streams for packet encapsulation.

### 5. Reset the Stream, Keep the Keyframe: Reliable Boundaries in Media over QUIC
* **Presentation:** [Reset the Stream, Keep the Keyframe](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/126/materials/slides-126-anrw-transport-and-media-reset-the-stream-keep-the-keyframe-01)
* **Presenter:** Sebastian (Rashaan)
* **Discussion:**
  * Sebastian discussed low-latency live streaming over Media over QUIC (MoQ). Under congestion, standard QUIC stream resets discard partially transmitted data, resulting in lost keyframes and wasted bandwidth.
  * The authors proposed using the QUIC reliable stream reset extension (`draft-ietf-quic-reliable-stream-reset` / `RESET_STREAM_AT`) to define reliable boundaries. Two strategies were tested: setting the boundary directly after the keyframe, or protecting up to the last fully written object.
  * Emulated network results demonstrated that protecting keyframes bounded playback stall times to approximately one Group of Pictures (GOP) size (~1 second) and prevented complete feed freezes, without incurring a significant latency penalty.
  * **Q&A:**
    * Gorry Fairhurst asked if varying video scenes (which change the ratio of keyframe to P-frame sizes) impacted the results. Sebastian noted that while they tested this privately, different sceneries heavily change P-frame sizes and must be matched with appropriate link capacities.
    * Lucas Pardew noted that the reliable stream reset draft had just progressed to IETF Last Call. He asked about the scheduling of retransmissions. Sebastian replied that prioritizing fresh data over retransmissions is an active area of investigation.

### 6. Multiplexing Synchronized Media in Watch Parties
* **Presentation:** [Multiplexing Synchronized Media](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/126/materials/slides-126-anrw-transport-and-media-multiplexing-synchronized-media-00)
* **Presenter:** Ali Begen
* **Discussion:**
  * Ali Begen addressed the "Watch Party" use case, where users view synchronized video streams while participating in a real-time video conference.
  * Traditional implementations rely on a "Frankenstein" architecture of HTTP Live Streaming (HLS)/DASH for media playback alongside WebRTC for real-time video conferencing. This requires maintaining two separate protocol stacks that compete for bandwidth.
  * The authors introduced **Mocktail**, an open-source MoQ implementation using a unified QUIC connection. It separates traffic into a high-priority "context pipe" (main media) and low-to-medium-priority "excitement pipes" (participant audio/video), governed by a single congestion control state. If bandwidth drops, the lower-priority participant video and audio are dynamically discarded first to ensure the main media remains synchronized.
  * **Q&A:**
    * Lars Eggert asked if they had comparative numerical results proving the superiority of this unified stack over WebRTC/HLS. Ali Begen confirmed that detailed experimental results are documented in the paper.

### 7. Tokens, Not Packets: An Upfront Scheduling Model for Multipath QUIC
* **Presentation:** [Tokens, Not Packets](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/126/materials/slides-126-anrw-transport-and-media-tokens-not-packets-00)
* **Presenter:** Max
* **Discussion:**
  * Max argued that existing Multipath QUIC (MPQUIC) schedulers behave as per-packet decision engines. This approach is tightly coupled with the protocol stack and limits advanced features like explicit control frame scheduling, application-aware data multiplexing, and redundant retransmissions.
  * The proposed "Tokens, Not Packets" model moves scheduling decisions upfront. The scheduler outputs persistent, multi-level token queues (control and data tokens) based on connection state snapshots. This cleanly encapsulates the scheduling logic and allows the application to control path selection dynamically.
  * **Q&A:**
    * Gorry Fairhurst thanked the presenter and noted that this upfront scheduling approach is a highly interesting alternative for the community.

### 8. Quantifying QoE-Aware Resource Sharing Potential
* **Presentation:** [Quantifying QoE-Aware Resource Sharing](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/126/materials/slides-126-anrw-transport-and-media-quantifying-qoe-aware-resource-sharing-00)
* **Presenter:** Sebastian Rado
* **Discussion:**
  * Sebastian Rado presented an analysis of QoE-aware resource allocation for real-time interactive video (e.g., cloud gaming, XR, remote machinery control). 
  * The study argued that allocating equal bitrates (flow-rate fairness) is a poor proxy for equal spatial quality because video spatial complexity varies by up to an order of magnitude within a single session.
  * By defining a utility function over VMAF and reallocating capacity second-by-second using statistical multiplexing (leveraging the fact that different streams' complex scenes rarely align), the required bottleneck capacity can be dramatically reduced. 
  * Under an ideal oracle, dynamic quality-based allocation required only 35 Mbps to keep 30 sessions acceptable (VMAF > 50), whereas static peak-rate allocation or rate fairness required more than 100 Mbps.
  * **Q&A:**
    * Gorry Fairhurst thanked the presenter for providing a comprehensive dataset on this topic.

### 9. An Open Source Implementation of IETF Transport Services (TAPS)
* **Presentation:** [An Open Source Implementation of IETF Transport Services](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/126/materials/slides-126-anrw-transport-and-media-an-open-source-implementation-of-ietf-transport-services-01)
* **Presenter:** Ingrid Tovin
* **Discussion:**
  * Ingrid Tovin introduced **CTAPs**, the first open-source C-based implementation of the IETF Transport Services (TAPS) architecture (`draft-ietf-taps-arch`, `draft-ietf-taps-api`) to include native QUIC support.
  * CTAPs abstractly exposes features from RFC 9000 (such as connection migration and path racing) through a unified, callback-based user-space API. This enables applications to transition between TCP, UDP, and QUIC without rebuilding the application code.
  * **Q&A:**
    * Michaud asked about the deployment model of CTAPs. Ingrid Tovin clarified that CTAPs resides in user-space above standard sockets and requires no cooperative changes from network operators.
    * Thomas Witt asked how this open standardized implementation positions itself against proprietary, vendor-locked network APIs. Ingrid Tovin answered that implementing the open TAPS RFCs in an open-source library democratizes these transport layer capabilities.

